column531: Call with Kara: Attendees: Khuram & Kara Demo Feedback: PPR Separate State / County Dropdowns: One of her students had recommended selecting the state and then the county so she was happy to see the feedback implemented. Nudge Feature: Liked it a lot. Milestone Mapper No feedback. Didn't like it or hate it. Analytics Career Cluster Distribution Pie Chart (She really loved this feature) Question: Can I see which students picked that career cluster? Yes, in the table. Liked: Not just the major they’re exploring but their pathways. Feature Request: Want to download it as a .CSV and filter? KZ: Yes you already can! Showed her how to download the .CSV and will send it to her so she can fill it out. KS: This is great! I can export the CSV and copy / paste the student IDs and paste it into their Grace system. I can then write passes and invite them to an event.   KS: This is great! If they’re military, want to have them meet with recruiters. If there’s a college fair, I can target the kids interested in colleges. Currently, I can see if they’re interested in a college but not the specific field. A school might have a specific program (ex: Sam Houston Criminal Justice), they can invite them. On my Grace platform, I can put it in if they’re interested in a school. However, that section is also with the college application section. If I knew general funds (like an artsy college is visiting, I can get the students). I can tag their 4 year post-secondary plans and filter but I can’t put their interests unless I’m adding a major but it’s easier to do it by field that majors so clusters which we don’t have. Question: How does it work with CTE? A lot of our community colleges have a lot of trade programs and we push them for a 2 year degree. A lot of that trade school falls into college according to that metric. A lot of students will pursue automotive. What would you like to see added to this? Really liked pathway distribution: Wants to be able to select by grade. Why? So they can see their interests changing. Maybe 9th grade is unknown and then 10th grade they can see it increased desire for college. They want to know why is it increasing? This year had a good chunk of kids choose 2 year college vs 4 year college b/c of fafsa changes. Wants to see differences in grades. Sometimes kid’s mindsets are changing due to tik tok videos. What would you like to see this removed? Don’t think so. Really wants to zoom in on Career Cluster Distribution. Principal Meeting KZ: Do you think we're ready to meet with the Principal? KS: I think it’s good enough to present. Run through it. Talk about how you're planning to incorporate it into classroom presentations and 1 on 1s. More than just a conversation with students. Maybe add a notes section to edit? KS: If Northside can utilize it, she can leverage it to get Forth Worth ISD. Xello has too much going on and it’s not easy to digest. PPR is easy to work.   KS: I’m happy to incorporate this with stuff we’re doing. I found out 2-3 weeks ago we’re working with 10th grade now so I will add an advisor and have a total 4 advisors. Happy to incorporate the PPR to beta test it. KS: Are you trying to use Northside as a guinea pig or get a contract? KZ: What would a price be that didn’t wouldn’t cause sticker shock? KS: It's very sensitive right now to talk about money at all. Northside is really pinching pennies because of the new superintendent. 17 principals just quit. Our district is going through a lot. They’re dipping into reserves for $17M for teacher raises. There’s $14M to $15M deficit. District is cutting so many people. Some schools in elementary and middle school don’t even have full time librarians. The district spent $45M on an admin building that doesn't really do much so they’re under a lot of scrutiny and any new initiatives will be scrutinized. TCC is doing these presentations, why would they need to spend more on college and career readiness. If something isn’t necessary in their eyes, they won’t invest in it. A lot of teachers are trying to head out. KZ: When do you think we can meet with Principal Martinez? KS: Martinez, her principal, was supposed to retire, but he will stick around for another year. He will be here for at least a half-year until December. She’ll also be there one more year. That’s her 5th year at TCU. Asked for a job. She will set up a meeting in the next three weeks. Feature Requests Career Cluster Pie Chart: Add dropdowns that allow the counselor to filter by grade so they can see which career clusters students are picking Allow the user to view the records for the selected slice (i.e. if the pie chart has healthcare, allow the user to hover or click on it and then view all of the students that chose that career cluster) Student Table Export Add a notes column Add a timestamp Sales Strategy Get a deal with Northside HS for 1-2 years, successful case study, and then grow to Fort Worth ISD Flagged Issue: Will the district have funding? Next Steps KZ will send Kara the .csv of the pathway analytics KS will set up a meeting (on campus for the next 3 weeks);58533543476;@Marc Steren @Khuram Zaman @Tremain Davis Marc, Tremain and Brandy met with Kara at North Side HS. We discussed a pilot with VIC for her and her students to use in order to better train VIC with specific questions, get feedback, data etc. She said the hardest part of her day is seeing having enough time to see all of her students. She works in the Go Center, where she is responsible for students filling out and turning in FAFSA as well as making sure they have a plan if they are going to college. VIC would be a great tool for her, her students and parents to use. It will be great to have a tool that students can access at any time and ease some anxiety if they don’t have much knowledge surrounding the issue. There is a larger Spanish speaking population at the school. We discussed using it for her Junior class starting in February. She did mention that some of her students come to her and they don't have an idea of what they want to do, what they like, what to major in. We want to put the "Holland Codes" personality assessment in Vic so students can use it as well. She said that she can give us some FAQ's that we can put in to "train" Vic to answer. **Need to set up a follow up meeting with Kara, Khuram and Brandy to discuss implementation We would like to ask her: How are her students using Xello. Grace platform;Antonio Martinez / Kara Stribling (Northside HS, Texas) Attendees Antonio Martinez Kara Stribling TD KZ Intros Summer School: Last day of summer school is next Tuesday. They'll be shutting down. They work year round. Statement Assessment Kara's last day is tomorrow until August, then transition to TCU, then 6 weeks of training. Kara: PPR is not just a career assessment, but a tailored response. Show's personalized pathway for Tarrant County. Chatbot: Only programmed to answer career questions. Demo Likes the fact it goes to the county Localization Cost: If we wanted to roll this out, how much would it cost?" TD:  $299/annual subscription. Antonio: "I can pay that out of the pocket." TD: Would love to roll it out in the fall. Kara: Get it set up. AM: "Count us in, we would love to a part of this." Just another tool. We also have build in our schedule every day for 20 minutes, we do different things. Go on it and spend your time. TD: Sometimes we'll have an FAQ. Kara: A lot of students don't know they're in Tarrant County. Maybe we can have it by city and then it autopopulates the county. Antonio: Do you do PO's through school districts? In most districts, we do purchase order. Y'all will need to be a vendor. Register as an ISD Vendor. Antonio: "I'm looking forward to hearing the chatter on campus. Sounds like you guys built a great program." Next Steps Get registered as a vendor in ISD (TD will work with Traci on this) Email Kara re fall rollout strategy (Khuram will call John and see how deployments should handle this) @Marc Steren @J Jabara @Tremain Davis

column531: About Dr. O'Shields Dr. O'Shields is a proud product of Laurens County School District 56. He graduated from Clinton High School in 1976. He went to the University of South Carolina and graduated with degrees in History and Religious Studies. He continued at USC and earned an MAT in History in 1982. He taught for two years at WA Perry Middle School in Columbia (Richland County School District 1) before returning home in 1984. He taught social studies and developed and taught the interdisciplinary gifted program for five years at Bell Street Middle School. In 1988, Mr. O'Shields completed his Masters in Gifted Education from Converse College. In 1989, Mr. O'Shields had the privilege and opportunity to return to Clinton High as assistant principal. Under the tutelage of Dr. Keith Bridges, Mr. O'Shields served as Assistant Principal for Curriculum and Student Activities. During his eight years at CHS, Mr. O'Shields had the opportunity to complete his PhD at Clemson University in Educational Leadership. In 1997, Dr. O'Shields returned to his former elementary school, Clinton Elementary, and served as principal for two years. In 1999, Dr. O'Shields returned to his former middle school, Bell Street Middle School, to serve as principal for seven years. In 2006, Dr. O'Shields moved to the district office. He later became the Director of Human Resources (2007 - 2009) and eventually interim superintendent on October 1, 2009. On March 1, 2011, Dr. O'Shields was named Superintendent of Laurens County School District 56. Dr. O'Shields is humbled and honored to serve in the district that offered him the opportunities to pursue his educational aspirations and achieve his dreams. Dr. O'Shields wants all parents and students to know our small district casts a large presence in the state. Thanks to the dedicated professionals in Laurens County School District 56, our students excel in academics, athletics, the fine arts, and extracurricular activities.;Schedule a district office conference room His wife is the career person in the county - she has been very sick and had surgery 3 elementary school - 99/ month 1 middle school 199/month 1 high school 199/month transitions materials

column531: scheduled a dinner with her and her team - as well and TD, MS and EB she is attending this conference https://osepideasthatwork.org/osep-meeting/2024-osep-conference;https://nmeducation.org/margaret-cage-appointed-as-new-special-education-director-in-new-mexico/ Margaret Cage Appointed as New Special Education Director in New Mexico After a five month search, the New Mexico Public Education Department has named Margaret Cage as its new Special Education Director. Cage brings more than  25 years of experience in education, has held various roles in the field including: teacher, instructional coach, turnaround specialist, school leader, and school system director. Just before stepping into this role, Cage was the special education supervisor for Assumption Parish Schools in Louisiana. Cage, who assumed her role October 4, was selected after an extensive nationwide search, and her appointment was met with enthusiasm from a variety of educators and officials. “Dr. Cage is the leader everyone involved was most excited about,” said state education Secretary Arsenio Romero, adding that “she brings enthusiasm, experience, and the will to get the work done.” In response to her appointment, Cage expressed her eagerness to make a positive impact on the lives and communities of New Mexico. “I am elated to have been chosen for this position and for the opportunity to make a difference and impact the lives and communities of New Mexico,” she said. Cage holds a Bachelor of Science in Pre-Law from Nicholls State University in Thibodaux, Louisiana, along with certifications and degrees in special education, educational leadership, and executive educational leadership from The University of Holy Cross in New Orleans, Louisiana. Governor Michelle Lujan Grisham established the Office of Special Education earlier this year through an executive order. The goal, according to the governor’s office, is to enhance collaboration between state agencies, districts, and families of students with special needs, and improve the quality of special education services in New Mexico. This executive order came after a legislative battle failed, aiming to codify this office into state law. Originally championed by State Representative Liz Thomson (D – Bernalillo), the legislation faced an immediate uphill battle when it received a “do not pass recommendation” from the House Education Committee. After some changes to the initial bill were made by the committee, it received a “Do Pass” recommendation. This was only the beginning of the bill’s difficulties; after the bill received a “do pass” recommendation from the House Government, Elections, and Indian Affairs Committee it failed to ever be scheduled for a floor vote. “One of the things that I pride myself on is being a change agent and a transformational leader,” Cage said, “I am always thinking about the possibilities, seeking solutions, and committed to taking something that may not be positive and improving it.” NMPED announces Margaret Cage, Ed.D, as Special Education Director Tuesday, 03 October 2023 20:43 gallupsun The New Mexico Public Education Department has appointed Margaret Cage, Ed.D, as the new Special Education Director. Cage, who will began work Oct. 2, has spent over 25 years in education, serving as a teacher, instructional coach, turnaround specialist, school leader, and school system director. She has invested her career in transforming schools and school systems to improve the futures and lives of all students. She holds a Bachelor of Science in Pre-Law from Nicholls State University in Thibodaux, Louisiana, a Certification in Special Education, a Master of Educational Leadership, and a Doctorate of Executive Educational Leadership from The University of Holy Cross in New Orleans. "We conducted an extensive nationwide search for the best person to do this critical work at the PED, and Dr. Cage is the leader everyone involved was most excited about. She brings enthusiasm, experience, and the will to get the work done. I am so excited she is here and ready to get to work," NMPED Secretary Arsenio Romero said. Gov. Michelle Lujan Grisham created The Office of Special Education through Executive Order in May. "This office creates an opportunity for collaboration between state agencies, districts and families of students that we desperately need and that the 50,000 New Mexico children in special education deserve," Lujan Grisham said when she signed the executive order. "We are doing more to improve the quality of special education students receive by ensuring families are better supported in navigating a complicated system and that teachers receive consistent, up-to-date training." In a press release published Oct. 2 Cage thanked the governor for the opportunity. "I am elated to have been chosen for this position and for the opportunity to make a difference and impact the lives and communities of New Mexico," she said."I think [this position] shows the deep commitment of the governor's office, the Public Education Department, and all the stakeholders supporting our efforts to do what's best for our children." She also stated that she's looking forward to joining the NMPED and helping make positive changes to the educational environment in New Mexico. "One of the things that I pride myself on is being a change agent and a transformational leader," she said. "I am always thinking about the possibilities, seeking solutions, and committed to taking something that may not be positive and improving it.";reach out to Jennifer, Rodriguez (505) 470-7898 jennifer.rodriguez1@ped.nm.gov Executive Secretary/Administrative Assistant;We need to look at indigenous languages: https://www.sos.nm.gov/voting-and-elections/native-american-election-information-program/native-american-languages-in-new-mexico/

column531: Mr. Morales called me today- Principal White is back from medical leave. They both thought the other checked in with me. The teachers last semester were "eh" about the Social Entrepreneurship class, but Mr. Morales said it got bogged down at the end of the year and conflicted with other priorities. Students weren't really prepared for pitch presentation, a lot of chasing down students to finish assignments. Said that it should be better this time around now that they know how it works. Discussed the last message from Zenobia which said to focus on 9th grade Career Exploration and SE. They have received curriculum around Career Exploration from the Future Ready NY program, but wouldn't hurt to have more resources. He said he may be able to get started on his after school Internship program, funding will come end of October He said he will touch base with Zenobia about Career Discovery and SE and get back to me. I offered to send catalog and provide a refresher training if needed, said we're ready to go when they are.

column512: Follow up with Bettye Wiley;status check 7/26;circle back - is contract signed? ;reach out
column531: Tami and I met with Bettye Wiley and her team of middle school counselors last week, as a follow-up to the in-person presentation Tremain and I had the previous week. We shared the CD courses. When I spoke to Bettye today, she provided lots of great feedback: 1. She is looking to implement a new career discovery/exploration program in the fall 2. Her counselors would like to see a more in-depth discovery process into each career cluster (think: this is agriculture week and we are going to zoom in on careers within this industry) 3. She likes the idea of having "day-in-the-life-of" videos She has agreed to meet with us in January to continue the conversation, and she could be a great potential partner to get inside the course and give lots of potentially useful feedback. She has only seen the short demo. Is this something we would be interested in? Would we consider implementing her feedback into our CD courses? Would that make a potential pilot program more interesting for us and for them? We are already scheduled for a "brainstorming" session on January 16th...;marc is going to follow up with bettye;2144762604

column531: OK this is very strange for all kinds of reasons. Erica, when you speak to Lakeisha tomorrow, can you see what can be done? For background. On May 17th I last spoke to Karen and she asked us to prepare the entrepreneurship course for fall and we deployed this, and we negotiated a much discounted renewal which they signed. Have not been able to get in touch with Karen since then. As you know, we custom built Daily SE and Daily FoW for Construction and trained their teachers extensively with personal visits, sent customers there for references, so our expectation was that these would become a regular part of the curriculum. If these courses were unsatisfactory, we are on standby to make any changes to meet their needs. Let me know what you find out. Thanks;response to john: Good Afternoon, Thank you for your correspondence. We currently do not have a course in need of the curriculum you are offering this Fall. We may however need the course starting in the spring semester or Fall 2025. Thanks again, Mrs. Karen Han Assistant Principal High School for Construction Trades, Engineering, & Architecture 94-06 104th st Ozone Park,NY 11416 718-846-6280 ext 2042

column531: Eva Morales- CTE teacher, interested in Impact Internship, Passion Project, Workforce Development, and High School Employment Search.;Spoke with Eva. Transition: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of Transition Planning for High School Students with Disabilities, we will improve Vocational and Transition Skills by a 5% increase from September to June, as measured by student progress on Transition Goals, SANDI Transition School and SANDI Transition Community. Asked to be connected with him later today or tomorrow, Jan.9th.;Zoom call with Dr. Ottey to continue the conversation for he and the 4 schools he supports. He is the Assistant Principal of and currently they are in a cost-cutting phase due to the new influx of immigrant children coming from Texas and Florida. They are cutting costs not only at the inner city schools but are also using some of the high schools who don't have high enrollment, as a housing situtation is prevelant and concerning in NYC right now. Dr. Ottey described it as a 'Crisis' and one that he has never seen in his many years in the Education space. The next steps are to reach out to him in Q3/Q4 as funding is non-existent right now and they are checking every piece of spend they do. He loves our program but also knows the Principal well enough that she isn't spending on any new projects/programs right now.;12/28/23 MBK grant received - 4 year granted Launch date is February for financial literacy initiative This will include 5 schools in two campuses = 5 deals Evander Campus (3 schools) Tuwett campus (2 schools) High priority for the district Wanting to change the narrative Investing money and resources in the community Workshops and culturally relevant meals (barbering, entrepreneurship and cosmetology) Community food distribution, fresh product Moon shot nights Trying to figure out the right group of students, also looking at financial literacy a little bit differently now, changing the relationship with money, looking at the big picture, what skills can you monetize, give them some tools to to get infant of the employment. For our teachers - thinking about the life term for this grant Earn Your Leisure - who men who have a. column531: K-12 school total number of students: HS - 220 MS - CEP Goals: https://p017x.org/cep.html IEP: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of IEPs for all Students with Disabilities, we will improve the completion of progress monitoring of IEP goals to 70% of students meeting their IEP goals as measured by the percentage of IEPs closed out in SESIS between September 2022 and June 2023. Transition: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of Transition Planning for High School Students with Disabilities, we will improve Vocational and Transition Skills by a 5% increase from September to June, as measured by student progress on Transition Goals, SANDI Transition School and SANDI Transition Community. Students with development disabilities: they are intersted Emily is going to reach out to me to get a time scheduled for next week;Hi Erica, Happy New Year! Unfortunately, there is no room in our schedule this year to incorporate more programs. Thank you for circling back, but at this time, our schedule is jampacked, and we will not be able to meet. Have a great day!;1/12/24 Erica, Tremain and Ms. Bailey met for a discovery meeting 400 students in middle school, grades 6 - 8 Erica introduces our team and takes notes about meeting Tremain introduces what we do, talks about 3 verticles Ms. Bailey listens  to Tremain and takes notes, Tremain emphasizes career clusters Questions for Ms. Bailey: What is your biggest challenge? What are you trying to solve? School of College and Career Exploration: Wants to gives students all of the options for careers and for college, both pathways are important Whats to know what the program looks like in terms of exposing students to as many pathways as possible Erica stayed on the call with her to show her some of our info We are scheduled to follow up Friday January 19th at 12:30pm @Tremain Davis @Jenae McPhatter;RETIRED;ADMINISTRATION Name Position Email Angela Jones Principal AJones80@schools.nyc.gov Emily Feller Asst. Principal Melissa Wright (Acting AP) mwright11@schools.nyc.gov;dnancino@schools.nyc.gov;january 16th - presentation for entire district in nyc;Laura Lee contacted Bill Fahey for an update on what the status and next steps are with USU!! Asked to be connected with him later today or tomorrow, Jan.9th.;Zoom call with Dr. Ottey to continue the conversation for he and the 4 schools he supports. He is the Assistant Principal of and currently they are in a cost-cutting phase due to the new influx of immigrant children coming from Texas and Florida. They are cutting costs not only at the inner city schools but are also using some of the high schools who don't have high enrollment, as a housing situtation is prevelant and concerning in NYC right now. Dr. Ottey described it as a 'Crisis' and one that he has never seen in his many years in the Education space. The next steps are to reach out to him in Q3/Q4 as funding is non-existent right now and they are checking every piece of spend they do. He loves our program but also knows the Principal well enough that she isn't spending on any new projects/programs right now.;12/28/23 MBK grant received - 4 year granted Launch date is February for financial literacy initiative This will include 5 schools in two campuses = 5 deals Evander Campus (3 schools) Tuwett campus (2 schools) High priority for the district Wanting to change the narrative Investing money and resources in the community Workshops and culturally relevant meals (barbering, entrepreneurship and cosmetology) Community food distribution, fresh product Moon shot nights Trying to figure out the right group of students, also looking at financial literacy a little bit differently now, changing the relationship with money, looking at the big picture, what skills can you monetize, give them some tools to to get infant of the employment. For our teachers - thinking about the life term for this grant Earn Your Leisure - who men who have a. Podcast, talking about how to leverage your finances to build wealth, Look at messaging to parent leaders and what that would look like When would you like to start? February for launch Erica needs to reach out to: Carmen Mercado - district 10 (the largest district) and Cristina Jimenez’s contact *send information to Cristina about our company and about TD @Tremain Davis @Tami Levey;Met 1/5/24 w/ Anahi Flores, the principal Ms Guillaume asked us to meet with her Graphic design, dual imaging, interested in college readiness and workforce development she is interested in everything we have to offer for high school 351 students at the school - we scheduled a demo for jan 12th at 1pm;SENATOR IWEN CHU'S DISTRICT;office of student pathways #718 557 2590 (pathways to graduation office) - could be her office, that would be the best bet  ;Erica/LL received an email from Sabene requesting a meeting at the end of January as opposed to the next few weeks. Erica/LL will send her a message next week to firm up that meeting.

column531: K-12 school total number of students: HS - 220 MS - CEP Goals: https://p017x.org/cep.html IEP: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of IEPs for all Students with Disabilities, we will improve the completion of progress monitoring of IEP goals to 70% of students meeting their IEP goals as measured by the percentage of IEPs closed out in SESIS between September 2022 and June 2023. Transition: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of Transition Planning for High School Students with Disabilities, we will improve Vocational and Transition Skills by a 5% increase from September to June, as measured by student progress on Transition Goals, SANDI Transition School and SANDI Transition Community. Principal Melissa Wright (Acting AP) mwright11@schools.nyc.gov;dnancino@schools.nyc.gov;january 16th - presentation for entire district in nyc;Laura Lee contacted Bill Fahey for an update on what the status and next steps are with USU!! Asked to be connected with him later today or tomorrow, Jan.9th.;Zoom call with Dr. Ottey to continue the conversation for he and the 4 schools he supports. He is the Assistant Principal of and currently they are in a cost-cutting phase due to the new influx of immigrant children coming from Texas and Florida. They are cutting costs not only at the inner city schools but are also using some of the high schools who don't have high enrollment, as a housing situtation is prevelant and concerning in NYC right now. Dr. Ottey described it as a 'Crisis' and one that he has never seen in his many years in the Education space. The next steps are to reach out to him in Q3/Q4 as funding is non-existent right now and they are checking every piece of spend they do. He loves our program but also knows the Principal well enough that she isn't spending on any new projects/programs right now.;12/28/23 MBK grant received - 4 year granted Launch date is February for financial literacy initiative This will include 5 schools in two campuses = 5 deals Evander Campus (3 schools) Tuwett campus (2 schools) High priority for the district Wanting to change the narrative Investing money and resources in the community Workshops and culturally relevant meals (barbering, entrepreneurship and cosmetology) Community food distribution, fresh product Moon shot nights Trying to figure out the right group of students, also looking at financial literacy a little bit differently now, changing the relationship with money, looking at the big picture, what skills can you monetize, give them some tools to to get infant of the employment. For our teachers - thinking about the life term for this grant Earn Your Leisure - who men who have a. Podcast, talking about how to leverage your finances to build wealth, Look at messaging to parent leaders and what that would look like When would you like to start? column531: Dr. Tessie Rose Bailey is the PROGRESS Center project director. In addition to this role, she serves as a national expert in special education, transition, and MTSS/RTI for states and districts through the National Center on Intensive Intervention and the National Center for Systemic Improvement as well as several state contracts. Prior to her current work, she served as a university faculty member, education consultant, and classroom special education teacher. Dr. Bailey has conducted hundreds of professional learning workshops and presentations on effective instruction and assessment practices for struggling students and students with disabilities, MTSS/RTI, special education law and policy, and transition services. She has developed tools and conducted national webinars related to academic IEP goal setting, the Endrew decision, and intensive intervention. She completed her PhD at the University of Utah in special education and did postdoctoral work in MTSS/RTI and secondary transition at Lehigh University’s Center for Promoting Research to Practice.

column531: Ideas in speaking with Marc: need training dates/ time lines pushing a contract out to her $50k;Daiana Iqbal Daiana Iqbal, Director of Manhattan TCAC diqbal@schools.nyc.gov Daiana is an accomplished manager and leader with over 20 years of experience successfully managing large-scale programs in education, health, emergency management and social services in both governmental and nonprofit settings. Daiana worked in city government for 16 years, at the Department of Health, where she led the development of the nascent 311 system.  Daiana later transitioned to NYCPS and for the past eleven years has held many leadership positions positions at the central division of Family and Community Engagement and currently led 5 election cycles for the Community and Citywide Education Councils (formerly school boards). She holds both a Masters degree in Social Work and a Masters degree in Business Administration. She is an entrepreneur in spirit and is looking forward to providing services on behalf of all borough students with disabilities. 11 years department of education Native language Romanian;TCAC - Transition and College Centers Public mental health Work based learning Community engagement manager with Transition College Access Centers TCAC Started on the basis of a law suit, to assist any student who receives special education services Special education - 2 areas of work build their capacity to work with Educator + transition team leader Instructionally we build capacities within schools We also ensure that students are college and career ready We employ career services

column531: K-12 school total number of students: HS - 220 MS - CEP Goals: https://p017x.org/cep.html IEP: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of IEPs for all Students with Disabilities, we will improve the completion of progress monitoring of IEP goals to 70% of students meeting their IEP goals as measured by the percentage of IEPs closed out in SESIS between September 2022 and June 2023. Transition: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of Transition Planning for High School Students with Disabilities, we will improve Vocational and Transition Skills by a 5% increase from September to June, as measured by student progress on Transition Goals, SANDI Transition School and SANDI Transition Community. Unfortunately, there is no room in our schedule this year to incorporate more programs. Thank you for circling back, but at this time, our schedule is jampacked, and we will not be able to meet. Have a great day!;1/12/24 Erica, Tremain and Ms. Bailey met for a discovery meeting 400 students in middle school, grades 6 - 8 Erica introduces our team and takes notes about meeting Tremain introduces what we do, talks about 3 verticles Ms. Bailey listens  to Tremain and takes notes, Tremain emphasizes career clusters Questions for Ms. Bailey: What is your biggest challenge? What are you trying to solve? Principal Melissa Wright (Acting AP) mwright11@schools.nyc.gov;@Katherine Zmoda nicole did not call me back, i tried several times - this is a lost cause;dnancino@schools.nyc.gov;january 16th - presentation for entire district in nyc;Laura Lee contacted Bill Fahey for an update on what the status and next steps are with USU!! Asked to be connected with him later today or tomorrow, Jan.9th.;Zoom call with Dr. Ottey to continue the conversation for he and the 4 schools he supports. He is the Assistant Principal of and currently they are in a cost-cutting phase due to the new influx of immigrant children coming from Texas and Florida. They are cutting costs not only at the inner city schools but are also using some of the high schools who don't have high enrollment, as a housing situtation is prevelant and concerning in NYC right now. Dr. Ottey described it as a 'Crisis' and one that he has never seen in his many years in the Education space. The next steps are to reach out to him in Q3/Q4 as funding is non-existent right now and they are checking every piece of spend they do. He loves our program but also knows the Principal well enough that she isn't spending on any new projects/programs right now.;12/28/23 MBK grant received - 4 year granted Launch date is February for financial literacy initiative This will include 5 schools in two campuses = 5 deals Evander Campus (3 schools) Tuwett campus (2 schools) High priority for the district Wanting to change the narrative Investing money and resources in the community Workshops and culturally relevant meals (barbering, entrepreneurship and cosmetology) Community food distribution, fresh product Moon shot nights Trying to figure out the right group of students, also looking at financial literacy a little bit differently now, changing the relationship with money, looking at the big picture, what skills can you monetize, give them some tools to to get infant of the employment. For our teachers - thinking about the life term for this grant Earn Your Leisure - who men who have a. Podcast, talking about how to leverage your finances to build wealth, Look at messaging to parent leaders and what that would look like When would you like to start? column531: Here are some notes from the meeting with Mr. Weber: -He needs the course catalog -He is looking to build out the next 3 years with programs/partnerships that can benefit the students (meeting towards the end of Feb.) -He is interested in entrepreneurship (Marc covered this) -He wants to get away from "credit recovery" courses over the summer and focus more on executive functioning classes/programs for students...Marc talked about the transition to MS and transition to HS courses -They are a "destination" school. So he wants students to get "acclimated" more quickly to be ready for what they do at their school. -Marc talked about "Building an Academic Resume," "Service Learning," and "passion project." -Mr. Weber wants to create a "blueprint" for other school districts to follow or to be able to expand their offerings that include other schools. -He did ask about cost ($1,000/school/month) -6700 students across the whole district -HS has 2100 students 9-12 -Act 158 (everyone has to have a plan for after graduation) -He said he has a good diversity of students choosing different outcomes, so there are a wide variety of needs. -Marc talked about coming down in person for a demo (get that scheduled)

column531: I provided the MOU/Partner agreement which has been signed. The Pricing Invoice was also given to Dr.Andino. Next steps is getting the P.O. from their finance department. Implementation will be coming from Ruth/requested by Erica.;From LL: (John--Please take the below as feedback from Dr.Andino Flohr and not something we need to react to right away). I saw her this morning and she asked that I pass along 2 things to anything they would need for future partnering with Academy of Public Relations: 1) They are 40% Hispanic students with an additional population coming in the next year. She is going to need/want some of our programs most definitely in Spanish. She did not clarify which ones, but said she would like to move more in that direction within the next year as she sees more students coming in under the ESL programs. 2) Dr. Andino Flohr's school is the Academy of Public Relations: She would love to see a course that has some programs giving her students an overview of how Public Relations works in various sectors. She knows it's not a 'right now' thing to add to the courses, but she is looking for something for programming for her students. Just sharing feedback and letting you know that she is really looking forward to working with us! Thanks, LL;40130405654;41168929200

column531: K-12 school total number of students: HS - 220 MS - CEP Goals: https://p017x.org/cep.html IEP: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of IEPs for all Students with Disabilities, we will improve the completion of progress monitoring of IEP goals to 70% of students meeting their IEP goals as measured by the percentage of IEPs closed out in SESIS between September 2022 and June 2023. Transition: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of Transition Planning for High School Students with Disabilities, we will improve Vocational and Transition Skills by a 5% increase from September to June, as measured by student progress on Transition Goals, SANDI Transition School and SANDI Transition Community. Students with development disabilities: they are intersted Emily is going to reach out to me to get a time scheduled for next week;1/12/24 Erica, Tremain and Ms. Bailey met for a discovery meeting 400 students in middle school, grades 6 - 8 Erica introduces our team and takes notes about meeting Tremain introduces what we do, talks about 3 verticles Ms. Bailey listens  to Tremain and takes notes, Tremain emphasizes career clusters Questions for Ms. Bailey: What is your biggest challenge? What are you trying to solve? School of College and Career Exploration: Wants to gives students all of the options for careers and for college, both pathways are important Whats to know what the program looks like in terms of exposing students to as many pathways as possible Erica stayed on the call with her to show her some of our info We are scheduled to follow up Friday January 19th at 12:30pm @Tremain Davis @Jenae McPhatter;meeting with her colleague dec 27 to talk about solutions for the district;RETIRED;ADMINISTRATION Name Position Email Angela Jones Principal AJones80@schools.nyc.gov Emily Feller Asst. Asked to be connected with him later today or tomorrow, Jan.9th.;12/28/23 MBK grant received - 4 year granted Launch date is February for financial literacy initiative This will include 5 schools in two campuses = 5 deals Evander Campus (3 schools) Tuwett campus (2 schools) High priority for the district Wanting to change the narrative Investing money and resources in the community Workshops and culturally relevant meals (barbering, entrepreneurship and cosmetology) Community food distribution, fresh product Moon shot nights Trying to figure out the right group of students, also looking at financial literacy a little bit differently now, changing the relationship with money, looking at the big picture, what skills can you monetize, give them some tools to to get infant of the employment. For our teachers - thinking about the life term for this grant Earn Your Leisure - who men who have a. Podcast, talking about how to leverage your finances to build wealth, Look at messaging to parent leaders and what that would look like When would you like to start? column531: Call 8/12/24: Attendees: Mashea @Tremain Davis @Khuram Zaman How We Met Khuram did a post on LinkedIn re Gen AI workshop at BSU A friend of Khuram at Paypal saw the post and he serves on a board with Mashea's husband and he introduced us About Mashea Former special education teacher at a Middle School in Williamsburg VA Opened up a next generation Kipp School in Midwest Worked at NYC DOE, knows the Chancellor very well. CEO of a Newark charter school (part of the $50M fund set up by Mayor Corey Booker and Mark Zuckerberg) Moved to DC due to husband's work Full Background: https://www.linkedin.com/in/mashea-ashton-8b349b23/ About Digital Pioneer's Academy Mashea wanted to focus on middle school because she felt students began the decision to drop out in middle school and by high school it was too late to intervene Focused on computer science because she read an article saying there will be 1 million high paying jobs in computer science Two schools: Middle and high school which they launched during pandemic. They will graduate 1st class of seniors this year. Three part focus: (a) close education and job gap - her students do an average of 45 minutes of computer science every day, (b) wants scholars to become computational thinkers, and (c) unapologetic college prep. https://digitalpioneersacademy.org/ Pain Points Diminished Resources: She wants to focus on college readiness, but only has 3 resources (1 is new to teaching, 1 is a teacher but not a specialist in CCR, and her main CCR person is going on maternity leave).  he is looking for augmentation, not automation. Get Middle School Kids a College Counselor: Wants kids to have a college counselor as early as middle school. I have 13 year old twins in MD and DC in private school. In 7th grade, they sat down with a college counselor and it was a great experience. She wants her schools to do something similar in 6th grade. She wanted to have middle schoolers start with a college counselor in terms of leadership / activities. What I believe is by the end of 10th grade, kids know what path they are on. Internships / externships. They aren't ever taken off of a path (college / career path). I want to get back to that. How to convince kids that college is even an option for them: There are some kids who never want to go to college because no one else in their family did. Others are smart but the idea of going to another year school turns them off. USU Interest Very interested in courses and teacher notes. Her Questions: Can we start as early as 6th grade? What is your best partner school? What is the actual service / program provided? Her Concerns / Objections Overloaded: Worried that there might be too many options we present. Buy In: Wants her staff to be present so they can decide if they like the materials and will proceed Budget No discussion regarding budget, she wants her staff to meet first Next Steps She has two team members and wants to set up an introduction. Would like to put it on the calendar for next week or the week after. We will schedule a demo call and have her staff and also Tami on it. Analysis What worked: posting on linkedin, website (she saw our service offering and she was very excited about teachern notes), good fit (problem matches solution) What didn't work: not having a presentation (she got a bit overwhelmed), we demoed PPR and Cici and I was a bit all over the place. I didn't know how to demo the teacher notes. How do we improve: sales training, flow charts. Maybe having a clear set of questions to validate customer need and splitting of demo.;Email to Mashea: Mashea, It was wonderful connecting with you yesterday and listening about your impressive journey as an educator and learning about the bold vision you have for Digital Pioneers Academy. Your focus on computer science is a testament to your leadership. Whether it is college and career readiness or generative AI, we would love to help assist you and your team on helping your middle school and high school students pursue a pathway to college and employment in tech. I've attached a flyer for our Career Discovery 1, 2, and 3 courses that go into more details about the programming. You mentioned that you would like to have your team meet us in the upcoming weeks. I've ccd Tremain (who you met on the call) and also Tami (who you haven't met yet). How does the week of August 26th look for you and your team? Is there a good day or time that works best for everyone? Regards,

IMPACT Internship, Workforce readiness,;@Tremain Davis Thomas Rosa- article 113 East 4th Street, Manhattan, NY 10003(Open external link) Spoke to Dean of Students- Thomas Rosa.. mentioned they work with other schools! (sister schools) Manhattan School for Career Development, 751M,  is a vibrant learning community that endorses equity and access for all students. Our program invites diverse learners who strive towards academic success towards college and career readiness. Through a rigorous combination of academics, inclusive education, vocationally-based training, cooperative learning experiences, and authentic internship-based community learning programs, we provide age appropriate curriculum that is aligned to the NYS Next Generation Standards. Our vision is for students to successfully compete in the global and digital marketplace. We are known for raising the standards of excellence in Special Education by providing various options that fit the individual needs of our learners, including: Middle School Preparatory High School Career Academy Main Campus Alternative Assessment NYS Next Generation standards Academic & CTE Courses Manhattan Transition Center Community-Based Vocational Internships [Manhattan & Bronx] CTE: Co-op Tech Inclusive Education High School of Fashion Industries Harvey Milk High School Hudson High School of Learning Technologies

column531: 8/10/23 zoom call John, Ruth, Vinette, Ms. Moore Special needs middle and high school with 2 locations. Students come in for 40 minute sessions 1-2x per week, paired up 4 at a time with support staff for learning. Want USU to provide content for these sessions. Ideally at the 3rd grade reading level, but if not, use Live Notes to have teachers make adjustments. There is also an after school program TOP that meets 2x week for 2 hours and they would like us to submit a proposal  in due course. For Fall TSH (6 students) TMS (3 students) College Counseling Essays Career Discovery 1-3 How to Use Canvas Need to build Canvas instance, and send over White List. School to send over list of teachers to be added to courses. Deliver by 9/5 as teachers have time blocked off to review. Training date to be determined later once schedule becomes clear.;Training dates; week of the 14th have two rotations/trainings for teacher coverage. Training will happen during school hours. column531: K-12 school total number of students: HS - 220 MS - CEP Goals: https://p017x.org/cep.html IEP: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of IEPs for all Students with Disabilities, we will improve the completion of progress monitoring of IEP goals to 70% of students meeting their IEP goals as measured by the percentage of IEPs closed out in SESIS between September 2022 and June 2023. Transition: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of Transition Planning for High School Students with Disabilities, we will improve Vocational and Transition Skills by a 5% increase from September to June, as measured by student progress on Transition Goals, SANDI Transition School and SANDI Transition Community. Students with development disabilities: they are intersted Emily is going to reach out to me to get a time scheduled for next week;Zoom call with Dr. Ottey to continue the conversation for he and the 4 schools he supports. He is the Assistant Principal of and currently they are in a cost-cutting phase due to the new influx of immigrant children coming from Texas and Florida. They are cutting costs not only at the inner city schools but are also using some of the high schools who don't have high enrollment, as a housing situtation is prevelant and concerning in NYC right now. Dr. Ottey described it as a 'Crisis' and one that he has never seen in his many years in the Education space. The next steps are to reach out to him in Q3/Q4 as funding is non-existent right now and they are checking every piece of spend they do. He loves our program but also knows the Principal well enough that she isn't spending on any new projects/programs right now.;12/28/23 MBK grant received - 4 year granted Launch date is February for financial literacy initiative This will include 5 schools in two campuses = 5 deals Evander Campus (3 schools) Tuwett campus (2 schools) High priority for the district Wanting to change the narrative Investing money and resources in the community Workshops and culturally relevant meals (barbering, entrepreneurship and cosmetology) Community food distribution, fresh product Moon shot nights Trying to figure out the right group of students, also looking at financial literacy a little bit differently now, changing the relationship with money, looking at the big picture, what skills can you monetize, give them some tools to to get infant of the employment. For our teachers - thinking about the life term for this grant Earn Your Leisure - who men who have a. Podcast, talking about how to leverage your finances to build wealth, Look at messaging to parent leaders and what that would look like When would you like to start? column531: K-12 school total number of students: HS - 220 MS - CEP Goals: https://p017x.org/cep.html IEP: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of IEPs for all Students with Disabilities, we will improve the completion of progress monitoring of IEP goals to 70% of students meeting their IEP goals as measured by the percentage of IEPs closed out in SESIS between September 2022 and June 2023. Transition: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of Transition Planning for High School Students with Disabilities, we will improve Vocational and Transition Skills by a 5% increase from September to June, as measured by student progress on Transition Goals, SANDI Transition School and SANDI Transition Community. Have a great day!;1/12/24 Erica, Tremain and Ms. Bailey met for a discovery meeting 400 students in middle school, grades 6 - 8 Erica introduces our team and takes notes about meeting Tremain introduces what we do, talks about 3 verticles Ms. Bailey listens  to Tremain and takes notes, Tremain emphasizes career clusters Questions for Ms. Bailey: What is your biggest challenge? What are you trying to solve? School of College and Career Exploration: Wants to gives students all of the options for careers and for college, both pathways are important Whats to know what the program looks like in terms of exposing students to as many pathways as possible Erica stayed on the call with her to show her some of our info We are scheduled to follow up Friday January 19th at 12:30pm @Tremain Davis @Jenae McPhatter;RETIRED;ADMINISTRATION Name Position Email Angela Jones Principal AJones80@schools.nyc.gov Emily Feller Asst. Principal Melissa Wright (Acting AP) mwright11@schools.nyc.gov;dnancino@schools.nyc.gov;january 16th - presentation for entire district in nyc;Laura Lee contacted Bill Fahey for an update on what the status and next steps are with USU!! Asked to be connected with him later today or tomorrow, Jan.9th.;Zoom call with Dr. Ottey to continue the conversation for he and the 4 schools he supports. He is the Assistant Principal of and currently they are in a cost-cutting phase due to the new influx of immigrant children coming from Texas and Florida. They are cutting costs not only at the inner city schools but are also using some of the high schools who don't have high enrollment, as a housing situtation is prevelant and concerning in NYC right now. Dr. Ottey described it as a 'Crisis' and one that he has never seen in his many years in the Education space. The next steps are to reach out to him in Q3/Q4 as funding is non-existent right now and they are checking every piece of spend they do. He loves our program but also knows the Principal well enough that she isn't spending on any new projects/programs right now.;12/28/23 MBK grant received - 4 year granted Launch date is February for financial literacy initiative This will include 5 schools in two campuses = 5 deals Evander Campus (3 schools) Tuwett campus (2 schools) High priority for the district Wanting to change the narrative Investing money and resources in the community Workshops and culturally relevant meals (barbering, entrepreneurship and cosmetology) Community food distribution, fresh product Moon shot nights Trying to figure out the right group of students, also looking at financial literacy a little bit differently now, changing the relationship with money, looking at the big picture, what skills can you monetize, give them some tools to to get infant of the employment. For our teachers - thinking about the life term for this grant Earn Your Leisure - who men who have a. Podcast, talking about how to leverage your finances to build wealth, Look at messaging to parent leaders and what that would look like When would you like to start? February for launch Erica needs to reach out to: Carmen Mercado - district 10 (the largest district) and Cristina Jimenez’s contact *send information to Cristina about our company and about TD @Tremain Davis @Tami Levey;Met 1/5/24 w/ Anahi Flores, the principal Ms Guillaume asked us to meet with her Graphic design, dual imaging, interested in college readiness and workforce development she is interested in everything we have to offer for high school 351 students at the school - we scheduled a demo for jan 12th at 1pm;SENATOR IWEN CHU'S DISTRICT;office of student pathways #718 557 2590 (pathways to graduation office) - could be her office, that would be the best bet  ;Erica/LL received an email from Sabene requesting a meeting at the end of January as opposed to the next few weeks. column531: K-12 school total number of students: HS - 220 MS - CEP Goals: https://p017x.org/cep.html IEP: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of IEPs for all Students with Disabilities, we will improve the completion of progress monitoring of IEP goals to 70% of students meeting their IEP goals as measured by the percentage of IEPs closed out in SESIS between September 2022 and June 2023. Transition: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of Transition Planning for High School Students with Disabilities, we will improve Vocational and Transition Skills by a 5% increase from September to June, as measured by student progress on Transition Goals, SANDI Transition School and SANDI Transition Community. Students with development disabilities: they are intersted Emily is going to reach out to me to get a time scheduled for next week;1/12/24 Erica, Tremain and Ms. Bailey met for a discovery meeting 400 students in middle school, grades 6 - 8 Erica introduces our team and takes notes about meeting Tremain introduces what we do, talks about 3 verticles Ms. Bailey listens  to Tremain and takes notes, Tremain emphasizes career clusters Questions for Ms. Bailey: What is your biggest challenge? What are you trying to solve? School of College and Career Exploration: Wants to gives students all of the options for careers and for college, both pathways are important Whats to know what the program looks like in terms of exposing students to as many pathways as possible Erica stayed on the call with her to show her some of our info We are scheduled to follow up Friday January 19th at 12:30pm @Tremain Davis @Jenae McPhatter;meeting with her colleague dec 27 to talk about solutions for the district;RETIRED;ADMINISTRATION Name Position Email Angela Jones Principal AJones80@schools.nyc.gov Emily Feller Asst. Principal Melissa Wright (Acting AP) mwright11@schools.nyc.gov;dnancino@schools.nyc.gov;january 16th - presentation for entire district in nyc;Laura Lee contacted Bill Fahey for an update on what the status and next steps are with USU!! Asked to be connected with him later today or tomorrow, Jan.9th.;12/28/23 MBK grant received - 4 year granted Launch date is February for financial literacy initiative This will include 5 schools in two campuses = 5 deals Evander Campus (3 schools) Tuwett campus (2 schools) High priority for the district Wanting to change the narrative Investing money and resources in the community Workshops and culturally relevant meals (barbering, entrepreneurship and cosmetology) Community food distribution, fresh product Moon shot nights Trying to figure out the right group of students, also looking at financial literacy a little bit differently now, changing the relationship with money, looking at the big picture, what skills can you monetize, give them some tools to to get infant of the employment. For our teachers - thinking about the life term for this grant Earn Your Leisure - who men who have a. Podcast, talking about how to leverage your finances to build wealth, Look at messaging to parent leaders and what that would look like When would you like to start? February for launch Erica needs to reach out to: Carmen Mercado - district 10 (the largest district) and Cristina Jimenez’s contact *send information to Cristina about our company and about TD @Tremain Davis @Tami Levey;Met 1/5/24 w/ Anahi Flores, the principal Ms Guillaume asked us to meet with her Graphic design, dual imaging, interested in college readiness and workforce development she is interested in everything we have to offer for high school 351 students at the school - we scheduled a demo for jan 12th at 1pm;SENATOR IWEN CHU'S DISTRICT;DID NOT SHOW FOR RESCHEDULED MEETING TWICE;Erica/LL received an email from Sabene requesting a meeting at the end of January as opposed to the next few weeks. column531: K-12 school total number of students: HS - 220 MS - CEP Goals: https://p017x.org/cep.html IEP: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of IEPs for all Students with Disabilities, we will improve the completion of progress monitoring of IEP goals to 70% of students meeting their IEP goals as measured by the percentage of IEPs closed out in SESIS between September 2022 and June 2023. Transition: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of Transition Planning for High School Students with Disabilities, we will improve Vocational and Transition Skills by a 5% increase from September to June, as measured by student progress on Transition Goals, SANDI Transition School and SANDI Transition Community. Principal Melissa Wright (Acting AP) mwright11@schools.nyc.gov;dnancino@schools.nyc.gov;january 16th - presentation for entire district in nyc;Laura Lee contacted Bill Fahey for an update on what the status and next steps are with USU!! Asked to be connected with him later today or tomorrow, Jan.9th.;Zoom call with Dr. Ottey to continue the conversation for he and the 4 schools he supports. He is the Assistant Principal of and currently they are in a cost-cutting phase due to the new influx of immigrant children coming from Texas and Florida. They are cutting costs not only at the inner city schools but are also using some of the high schools who don't have high enrollment, as a housing situtation is prevelant and concerning in NYC right now. Dr. Ottey described it as a 'Crisis' and one that he has never seen in his many years in the Education space. The next steps are to reach out to him in Q3/Q4 as funding is non-existent right now and they are checking every piece of spend they do. He loves our program but also knows the Principal well enough that she isn't spending on any new projects/programs right now.;12/28/23 MBK grant received - 4 year granted Launch date is February for financial literacy initiative This will include 5 schools in two campuses = 5 deals Evander Campus (3 schools) Tuwett campus (2 schools) High priority for the district Wanting to change the narrative Investing money and resources in the community Workshops and culturally relevant meals (barbering, entrepreneurship and cosmetology) Community food distribution, fresh product Moon shot nights Trying to figure out the right group of students, also looking at financial literacy a little bit differently now, changing the relationship with money, looking at the big picture, what skills can you monetize, give them some tools to to get infant of the employment. For our teachers - thinking about the life term for this grant Earn Your Leisure - who men who have a. column531: K-12 school total number of students: HS - 220 MS - CEP Goals: https://p017x.org/cep.html IEP: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of IEPs for all Students with Disabilities, we will improve the completion of progress monitoring of IEP goals to 70% of students meeting their IEP goals as measured by the percentage of IEPs closed out in SESIS between September 2022 and June 2023. Transition: By June 2023, to strengthen the quality and implementation of Transition Planning for High School Students with Disabilities, we will improve Vocational and Transition Skills by a 5% increase from September to June, as measured by student progress on Transition Goals, SANDI Transition School and SANDI Transition Community. Students with development disabilities: they are intersted Emily is going to reach out to me to get a time scheduled for next week;1/12/24 Erica, Tremain and Ms. Bailey met for a discovery meeting 400 students in middle school, grades 6 - 8 Erica introduces our team and takes notes about meeting Tremain introduces what we do, talks about 3 verticles Ms. Bailey listens  to Tremain and takes notes, Tremain emphasizes career clusters Questions for Ms. Bailey: What is your biggest challenge? What are you trying to solve? School of College and Career Exploration: Wants to gives students all of the options for careers and for college, both pathways are important Whats to know what the program looks like in terms of exposing students to as many pathways as possible Erica stayed on the call with her to show her some of our info We are scheduled to follow up Friday January 19th at 12:30pm @Tremain Davis @Jenae McPhatter;meeting with her colleague dec 27 to talk about solutions for the district;RETIRED;ADMINISTRATION Name Position Email Angela Jones Principal AJones80@schools.nyc.gov Emily Feller Asst. Principal Melissa Wright (Acting AP) mwright11@schools.nyc.gov;dnancino@schools.nyc.gov;january 16th - presentation for entire district in nyc;Laura Lee contacted Bill Fahey for an update on what the status and next steps are with USU!! Asked to be connected with him later today or tomorrow, Jan.9th.;12/28/23 MBK grant received - 4 year granted Launch date is February for financial literacy initiative This will include 5 schools in two campuses = 5 deals Evander Campus (3 schools) Tuwett campus (2 schools) High priority for the district Wanting to change the narrative Investing money and resources in the community Workshops and culturally relevant meals (barbering, entrepreneurship and cosmetology) Community food distribution, fresh product Moon shot nights Trying to figure out the right group of students, also looking at financial literacy a little bit differently now, changing the relationship with money, looking at the big picture, what skills can you monetize, give them some tools to to get infant of the employment. For our teachers - thinking about the life term for this grant Earn Your Leisure - who men who have a. Podcast, talking about how to leverage your finances to build wealth, Look at messaging to parent leaders and what that would look like When would you like to start? February for launch Erica needs to reach out to: Carmen Mercado - district 10 (the largest district) and Cristina Jimenez’s contact *send information to Cristina about our company and about TD @Tremain Davis @Tami Levey;Met 1/5/24 w/ Anahi Flores, the principal Ms Guillaume asked us to meet with her Graphic design, dual imaging, interested in college readiness and workforce development she is interested in everything we have to offer for high school 351 students at the school - we scheduled a demo for jan 12th at 1pm;SENATOR IWEN CHU'S DISTRICT;DID NOT SHOW FOR RESCHEDULED MEETING TWICE;Erica/LL received an email from Sabene requesting a meeting at the end of January as opposed to the next few weeks. column531: W. T. White features high academic standards, a diverse student body, and a well-rounded program of educational and extracurricular activities. Several curriculum academies are available for students. The Academy of Business and Marketing, Academy of Engineering, and the Academy of Information Technology and Academy of Theatre Arts accept all interested students. The Pathway for Visual and Performing Arts requires all students to audition or submit a portfolio for consideration. The Pathway for Visual and Performing Arts includes band, choir, dance, orchestra, and visual arts; including ceramics. W. T. White graduates have been admitted to MIT, Harvard, Notre Dame, Stanford, Rice, UNC Chapel Hill, Carnegie Mellon, University of Texas, Texas Tech, Texas A & M, Baylor, SMU, TCU, and both Naval and Air Force Academies, to name a few of the many outstanding colleges and universities. The total scholarships and grants awarded for the graduating class of 2013 was more than $9.3 million and includes recipients of the Gates Millennium and Dell scholarships; including appointments to both the Naval and Air Force Academies. The W. T. White mission and motto speak to the high expectations we hold for all students. They have an academy of engineering Juan Almaraz-AP @Tremain Davis;Our meeting was successful and Mr. Almaraz says they need more support with career/college readiness first and workforce development second. He says they have used other programming in the past and they want something consistent and sustainable for their students. They are interested in data that shows our success with other clients/schools. I sent him the USU overview video and 2 different outcome reports. We will schedule the demo for 2 weeks from now. @Marc Steren @Tami Levey

column531: Focus Area: social entrepreneurship, passion project preparing an academic resume, college counseling Deal Amount:$5160 Potential Close Date:10/5/23 Can we update 430 students for 12 months starting in jan. 2024. 430 X 12 months =5160;No PTECh 430 Students Sole Source agreement Advisory period He doesn't want students to be able to just click through it 430/month purchase order;Tracy and I are working on applying for a "bid" with the procurement department at the district. The bid closes on 9/21 and we will hear back if we have been awarded a contract after that date. If we are awarded, we are authorized for 3 years guaranteed and any school in the district can use us. Contact is M. Scott in the procurement department.;Extension 5678?;We are working with Mr. Jewell and the financial clerk to get the purchase order. Tracy and I worked together to send all DISD required documents. Next step is to schedule implementation.;P.O (not partnership agreement);Discovery call with Marc went very well. Mr. Jewell is the AP for the Early College HS. He was joined by Caitlin Beauford, program coordinator at the community college (she serves Samuell HS). Mr. Jewell said that they need support in the areas of internships and workforce development. Because they are an early college HS and don't have a PTECH program, students can choose any pathway they want, however, it does not give students access to internships like a PTECH program does. His campus has about 430 students. They currently use Brightspace as their learning platform. He would like to have a more in depth discussion of the platform and see a proposal. Questions he asked were: What does the scale look like? How does it serve under resourced students? What is the cost? We will plan to meet with him in person next week. For the demo with Tami: -entrepreneurial mindset -impact internship -workforce development -Layout how it can be implemented over the four years of HS. @Tami Levey @Marc Steren

column531: Meeting with Ms. Gomez (Coordinator for Go Centers in FWISD) -Her main need is middle school/9th & 10th grade. -She feels they have strong programming for 11th/12th grade -Tremain did discovery, Tami showed a brief demo of Transition to HS, CD and focused on Middle School.  She shared VIC and gave a good overview of what our platform looks like. -Ms. Gomez is curious how it could be implemented and we discussed being a solo partner vs. partnering with other organizations Questions from Ms. Gomez: Are we in Texas and other districts Are the lessons customizable? yes Are parents able to access the modules? yes and parents can access VIC Different languages? Yes 24/7 Tutoring: no....(community colleges offer that, dual enrollment, what are the benefits) Canvas: Counseling/scheduling Cost? 37,000 students (MS, HS) Ms. Gomez will take it "up the chain" and wants to do another demo with the team. -CCMR directors (Robert Wright, Lisa Castillo) Specialty campuses: don't have outside resources Tremain mentioned discounts possible available Follow up will include sending info to Ms. Gomez that she can share with her team and we will schedule another demo;Adagui Gomez : Contact from Jazmin Chavez at TCC South/FWISD ECHS

Love this relationship---I can feel the sense of trust she has for USU. Well done all!" JJ: "Here is the plan for Talbot. Fall Transition to Middle School - Fall 6th grade Career Discovery - Fall 6, 7 and 8th grades Training 9/7 9-11am Send over courses, training materials one week in advance" TL: "Hi, John. Laura Lee and I had a great meeting with the supervisor for CTE of Dorchester County. I met with Anna Howie and her team several months ago with Tremain and Marc, so today was a follow-up. She is quite friendly with the administrators over at Talbot and was curious if they are piloting our CD program and if they are putting in students of all grades or just 6th graders? She is most interested in the middle school CD program as they have hired a career coach for all 3 of their middle schools within the county but have no curriculum developed! If you have any insight and what we might be able to share with her, that would be great. She absolutely LOVED the idea of a showcase and seemed potentially interested in a CTE-centered showcase (for high schoolers)."
